  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition" corresp="#Ed">
    <body>
      <div type="mūlam" rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TNV11">
      <l>murukiyaṅ kuṟuñci<anchor xml:id="kurinci"/> tuṭiyē pañcuram<anchor xml:id="pancuram"/></l>
<l>perukicai yēṟaṅ kōṭpaṟai<anchor xml:id="parai"/> tāram</l>
<l>palliya maruta<anchor xml:id="marutam"/> maḻappaṟai cevvaḻi</l>
<l>colliya piṟavuñ coṟṟavaṟ ṟicaiyē<anchor xml:id="icai"/></l>
</lg>
<p xml:lang="en">The <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Murukaṉ</hi></term> drum<note place="foot" xml:lang="en">As for how I have translated (or not translated) drum names, I decided to provide an english translation when the name clearly related to an action. In the other cases I have used their Tamil names. These are normally proper nouns that have no real english equivalent.</note> [and] the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Kuṟuñci</hi></term> [scale]<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">I have understood the the second respective item for each andscape to be a scale. This is roughly in keeping with what I understand the commentator suggests by designating them as <q xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">paṇ</hi></q>.</note>, the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Tuṭi</hi></term> drum [and] <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Pañcuram</hi></term> [scale],
the big bull-baiting drum [and] the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Tāram</hi></term> [scale],
many instruments [and] the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Marutam</hi></term> [scale], funeral drum [and] the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Cevvaḻi</hi></term> [scale]
and others mentioned [elsewhere are] mentioned as music.</p>
</div>
</body>
</text>
<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition" corresp="#Ed">
    <body>
      <head xml:lang="en">Commentary</head>
      <div type="commentary" rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="TNV11comm1">e-tu. icai yām āṟuṇarttutaṉutaliṟṟu.</p>
      <p xml:lang="en">The quoted [<term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">cūttiram</hi></term>] intends to make known the way music occurs.</p>
    </div>
    <div type="commentary" rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="TNV11comm2">veṟip paṟaiyuṅ kuṟuñcip paṇṇun tuṭiyum pañcurap paṇṇuṅ kōṭ paṟaiyun<anchor xml:id="kotparai"/> 
      tārap paṇṇunellari<anchor xml:id="nellari"/> kiṇaiyumutaṟ pal liyamumarutap paṇṇuneytaṟ paṟaiyuñ cevvaḻip paṇṇum uḷ ḷiṭṭaṉa 
      vain tiṇaikkum icai yām eṉṟa vāṟu.</p>
      <p xml:lang="en">The <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Veṟi</hi></term> drum and the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Kuṟuñci</hi></term> scale;
      the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Tuṭi</hi></term> drum and the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Pañcuram</hi></term> scale; the [bull-]seizing drum and the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Tāram</hi></term> scale; many instruments 
      beginning with the harvest drum and the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Marutam</hi></term> scale; <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Neytal</hi></term> 
      drum and the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">Cevvaḻi</hi></term> scale - they are included in the music for all the five tinais.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="commentary" rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="TNV11comm3">piṟavum eṉṟataṉāṟ ṟoṇṭakap<anchor xml:id="tontaka"/> paṟaiyum pūcaṟ<anchor xml:id="pucal"/> paṟaiyum vēyṅkuḻalum yāḻunāvāyp<anchor xml:id="navay"/> paṟaiyum uḷ ḷiṭṭaṉa vellāṅ koḷka.<anchor xml:id="kolka"/></p>
      <p xml:lang="en">Because he says "<term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">piṟavum</hi></term>", understand that all [of these] are included: 
      the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">toṇṭakam</hi></term> drum, the battle drum, the bamboo pipe, the <term xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">yāḻ</hi></term> and the seafaring drum.</p>
    </div>  
    </body>
